  "text": "The results of analysis of urine from the patients with NHL are shown in Table II . Assessment is more difficult in this case due to the heterogeneous nature of the disease and to the fact that therapy is often given. In the patients investigated, 7 out of 22 showed a monoclonal light chain. However, subsequent histological assessment showed that 3 patients (WW, PG and EF in Table II had rather than B lymphocytes, and a further 2 patients (RR and BW) had enlarged lymph nodes with the histological appearance of immunological reactivity rather than tumour involvement. One patient (JU) showed a histological appearance consistent with angioimmunoblastic lymphadenopathy. This is a lymphoproliferative disease not thought to involve neoplastic B lymphocytes [CITATION_1] , 1980) . In cells exporting an excess of free light chains it may be expected that they will appear eventually in the urine where they can both aid in diagnosis of a B cell tumour and also provide an index of tumour load [CITATION_2] . Methods used previously to examine urine for tumour-related light chains have relied on changes in the levels of one of the light chain types. Results then have to be interpreted against a wide range of KI/ ratios in normal subjects. Using such a procedure, significant increases in the level of one of the urinary light chain types were seen in 19 out of 76 cases of lymphoma and leukaemia (Lindstr6m et al., 1969) .",
